r_user":"runxiyu","user_is_author":false,"tags":["web"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ladobm","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ladobm/my_website_is_one_binary"},{"short_id":"sv6nzd","created_at":"2025-06-21T08:48:49.000-05:00","title":"Writing a basic Linux device driver when you know nothing about Linux drivers or USB","url":"https://crescentro.se/posts/writing-drivers/","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"w0nder1ng","user_is_author":false,"tags":["rust"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/sv6nzd","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/sv6nzd/writing_basic_linux_device_driver_when"},{"short_id":"4bn3cy","created_at":"2025-06-21T07:01:38.000-05:00","title":"Why computational reproducibility matters","url":"https://blog.khinsen.net/posts/2025/06/20/computational-reproducibility.html","score":8,"flags":0,"comment_count":5,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"fanf","user_is_author":false,"tags":["science"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/4bn3cy","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/4bn3cy/why_computational_reproducibility"},{"short_id":"5ubtft","created_at":"2025-06-21T05:33:12.000-05:00","title":"Scaling our Observability platform beyond 100 Petabytes by embracing wide events and replacing OTel","url":"https://clickhouse.com/blog/scaling-observability-beyond-100pb-wide-events-replacing-otel","score":5,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"knl","user_is_author":false,"tags":["performance"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/5ubtft","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/5ubtft/scaling_our_observability_platform"},{"short_id":"pfwzfa","created_at":"2025-06-21T05:23:04.000-05:00","title":"Open Dylan 2025.1 - Open Dylan Release","url":"https://opendylan.org/release-notes/2025.1.html","score":7,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"andreyorst","user_is_author":false,"tags":["lisp","release"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/pfwzfa","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/pfwzfa/open_dylan_2025_1_open_dylan_release"},{"short_id":"8ahj8b","created_at":"2025-06-21T05:01:57.000-05:00","title":"Unexpected security footguns in Go's parsers","url":"https://blog.trailofbits.com/2025/06/17/unexpected-security-footguns-in-gos-parsers/","score":29,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"knl","user_is_author":false,"tags":["go","security"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/8ahj8b","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/8ahj8b/unexpected_security_footguns_go_s"},{"short_id":"lwtxev","created_at":"2025-06-21T04:27:08.000-05:00","title":"Hare 0.25.2 released","url":"https://harelang.org/blog/2025-06-21-hare-0.25.2-released/","score":4,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"runxiyu","user_is_author":false,"tags":["plt","release"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/lwtxev","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/lwtxev/hare_0_25_2_released"},{"short_id":"5zj5e9","created_at":"2025-06-21T03:57:21.000-05:00","title":"Cosmoe: BeOS Class Library on top of Wayland","url":"https://cosmoe.org/index.html","score":18,"flags":0,"comment_count":3,"description":"\u003cp\u003eI don’t know if anyone remembers it, but way back there was a project called Cosmoe, which aimed to provide an implementation of the Haiku application environment on top of the Linux kernel. Turns out the author started working on it again.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ca href=\"https://gitlab.com/haydentech/cosmoe-wayland\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003e“new” flavour\u003c/a\u003e is slightly less ambitious – it doesn’t include the app_server and the registrar, it’s “just” a port of the BeOS class libraries on top of Linux and Wayland. The full port (now called Cosmoe Classic) also \u003ca href=\"https://gitlab.com/haydentech/cosmoe-haiku/\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003egot some updates\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBoth are pretty cool hacks. The new flavour is a pretty interesting example of how to (re-)implement an old-style UI library with contemporary tooling – though technically, it helps that Cairo is still contemporary tooling, I guess. The classic flavour is an even more interesting exercise in porting a bunch of non-Linux functionality.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTagging this \u003ccode\u003eretrocomputing\u003c/code\u003e since we don’t have a UI tag and I think BeOS qualifies as retrocomputing at this point :-). \u003ccode\u003eosdev\u003c/code\u003e seemed like a bit of a reach – the classic flavour is kind of there, I guess, but not quite the author’s main focus.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"I don't know if anyone remembers it, but way back there was a project called Cosmoe, which aimed to provide an implementation of the Haiku application environment on top of the Linux kernel. Turns out the author started working on it again.\r\n\r\nThe [\"new\" flavour](https://gitlab.com/haydentech/cosmoe-wayland) is slightly less ambitious -- it doesn't include the app_server and the registrar, it's \"just\" a port of the BeOS class libraries on top of Linux and Wayland. The full port (now called Cosmoe Classic) also [got some updates](https://gitlab.com/haydentech/cosmoe-haiku/).\r\n\r\nBoth are pretty cool hacks. The new flavour is a pretty interesting example of how to (re-)implement an old-style UI library with contemporary tooling -- though technically, it helps that Cairo is still contemporary tooling, I guess. The classic flavour is an even more interesting exercise in porting a bunch of non-Linux functionality.\r\n\r\nTagging this `retrocomputing` since we don't have a UI tag and I think BeOS qualifies as retrocomputing at this point :-). `osdev` seemed like a bit of a reach -- the classic flavour is kind of there, I guess, but not quite the author's main focus.","submitter_user":"x64k","user_is_author":false,"tags":["retrocomputing"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/5zj5e9","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/5zj5e9/cosmoe_beos_class_library_on_top_wayland"},{"short_id":"zibhyg","created_at":"2025-06-21T00:07:05.000-05:00","title":"In Praise of “Normal” Engineers","url":"https://charity.wtf/2025/06/19/in-praise-of-normal-engineers/","score":19,"flags":1,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"levlaz","user_is_author":false,"tags":["practices","programming"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/zibhyg","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/zibhyg/praise_normal_engineers"},{"short_id":"sht9yv","created_at":"2025-06-20T23:50:32.000-05:00","title":"The AGI economy is coming faster than you think","url":"https://www.freethink.com/artificial-intelligence/agi-economy","score":1,"flags":8,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"levlaz","user_is_author":false,"tags":["ai"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/sht9yv","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/sht9yv/agi_economy_is_coming_faster_than_you"},{"short_id":"urjnnp","created_at":"2025-06-20T23:44:14.000-05:00","title":"Of Course ML Has Monads! (2011)","url":"https://existentialtype.wordpress.com/2011/05/01/of-course-ml-has-monads/","score":5,"flags":0,"comment_count":2,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"icefox","user_is_author":false,"tags":["haskell","ml","plt"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/urjnnp","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/urjnnp/course_ml_has_monads_2011"},{"short_id":"xavw2b","created_at":"2025-06-20T20:10:17.000-05:00","title":"Why Can't We Break Cryptography?","url":"https://blog.computationalcomplexity.org/2025/04/why-cant-we-break-crytptography.html","score":2,"flags":1,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"teymour","user_is_author":false,"tags":["cryptography","math"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/xavw2b","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/xavw2b/why_can_t_we_break_cryptography"},{"short_id":"b1xxlr","created_at":"2025-06